00:04:42.780 --> 00:04:46.750
So protons, when they go
into the body, go into water,

00:04:46.750 --> 00:04:48.460
they have a very
different interaction

00:04:48.460 --> 00:04:51.850
with-- as they go through,
compared to say x-rays.

00:04:51.850 --> 00:04:55.040
So if x-rays go in, they deposit
most of their dose on their way

00:04:55.040 --> 00:04:57.700
in, and then they're dose rate
falls off as it goes deeper

00:04:57.700 --> 00:04:58.334
into the body.

00:04:58.334 --> 00:05:01.000
And the same is actually true of
electrons because they're light

00:05:01.000 --> 00:05:02.490
and they interact easily.

00:05:02.490 --> 00:05:04.560
The protons are heavier,
they have higher energy.

00:05:04.560 --> 00:05:06.510
They don't interact as easily.

00:05:06.510 --> 00:05:08.620
So they go in and they
don't deposit much energy,

00:05:08.620 --> 00:05:11.430
say something like
20% of the dose.

00:05:11.430 --> 00:05:13.544
But then the great
thing about protons

00:05:13.544 --> 00:05:15.960
is they actually slow down
towards the end of their range.

00:05:15.960 --> 00:05:19.950
And that dose level goes up and
you create this peak of dose

00:05:19.950 --> 00:05:22.490
at the very end of
the proton range.

00:05:22.490 --> 00:05:23.720
And then the protons stop.

00:05:23.720 --> 00:05:26.990
And we call this
shape the Bragg peak.

00:05:26.990 --> 00:05:30.450
And it's a very well
understood description

00:05:30.450 --> 00:05:33.540
in physics of how that works.

00:05:33.540 --> 00:05:36.430
So proton beams, you can
actually deliver a higher dose

00:05:36.430 --> 00:05:39.400
more accurately,
further into the body

00:05:39.400 --> 00:05:43.100
without damaging
surrounding tissue.

00:05:43.100 --> 00:05:45.300
And in order to tune
the depth of that peak

00:05:45.300 --> 00:05:46.800
and where it lands,
you just have

00:05:46.800 --> 00:05:49.186
to change the energy
of the incoming beam.

00:05:49.186 --> 00:05:52.590
